    {
      "id": "b06bcee55685f2eddcb209cf2e846e18ac61660e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-18 19:28:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nSo, does this mean a line count is incorrect and the small log record that is not counted the first time would make a valid log record after it to be incorrect? That sounds like a bug in itself",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "fe719493236d360f89143c32b833daafb16f5a83",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 101,
        "name": "Lai Siyao",
        "email": "lai.siyao@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "laisiyao"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-19 06:42:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIf the invalid message is shorter than sizeof(struct ptldebug_hdr), and it's at the end of the log file, it's not counted into bad line.\n\nThis test is as follows:\n1. dump a log file, modify some lines to bad format, and count bad lines.\n2. `cat log_good log_bad log_good > log_corrupt`, and then count bad lines.\n3. in step two, the short message is not at the end of log file, therefore it's not counted into bad lines.\n\nOleg, if you still think this is a bug for `lctl`, I will modify lctl code and re-submit a patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b7e804cb203e9104a34871d5a06db7d6d9d11b21",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2011-05-23 03:50:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me, approved\n\nOk, I reviewed the test code again and I think this is a correct approach.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
